{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491159","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491159"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:35:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:35:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"849"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/849"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.38,0.05,0.35,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"849"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53056"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/849"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"849"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38477"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"351"},{"type":"tags","id":"1198"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11116"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18658"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43825"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53056"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman attends her General Practitioner for follow-up, having been started on omeprazole two months earlier for heartburn. Despite managing to lose 5 kg body weight (BMI now 31kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E) and taking her medication regularly after meals (20mg BD), she still has symptoms. Whilst there has a been an improvement in her symptoms, she still experiences a retrosternal burning sensation that is worse when she lies flat. She has no other symptoms, no other significant medical history and the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Maintain current drug regimen and encourage further weight loss","Schedule the omeprazole for 30 minutes before meals","Change the omeprazole to pantoprazole","Endoscopy","24 hr pH and manometry"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAt this stage, there is very little to suggest that her symptoms are due to anything other than gastro-oesophageal reflux. The proton-pump inhibitors (PPI) are most effective if they are given prior to any stimulated acid secretion - i.e. \u003Cstrong\u003Ewell before meals\u003C/strong\u003E. She should still be encouraged to \u003Cstrong\u003Elose more weight.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is little evidence that changing the PPI (e.g. \u003Cstrong\u003Echanging omeprazole to pantoprazole) \u003C/strong\u003Ewill make much difference to the patient\u0027s symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAt this stage there is no need for any investigations to be undertaken. The patient does not have any alarm symptoms (haematemesis, melaena, dysphagia, odynophagia, vomiting, unintentional weight loss) and there is little to justify an \u003Cstrong\u003Eendoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003Cstrong\u003E24 hr pH and manometric studies\u003C/strong\u003E would only seriously be considered if the patient had proven and symptomatic gastro-oesophageal reflux disease that was not responding to medications and other conservative measures.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Unnecessary endoscopy should be avoided if the patient does not have any red flag symptoms."],"references":["Gastro-oesophageal reflux. In: Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd [online]. 2020. Available at: https://www.tg.org.au","Roman S, Gyawali CP, Savarino E, Yadlapati R, Zerbib F, Wu J, et al. Ambulatory reflux monitoring for diagnosis of gastro-esophageal reflux disease: Update of the Porto consensus and recommendations from an international consensus group. Neurogastroenterology and motility : the official journal of the European Gastrointestinal Motility Society. 2017;29(10):1-15. Available at: https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/nmo.13067"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38477"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"849"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38477","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38477"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-15T17:04:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-15T17:05:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"849"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53056"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"d